Figure 33 shows the solution of a particular, mildly relativistic Riemann problem for different values of the tangential velocity. The crossing point of any two lines in the upper panel gives the pressure and the normal velocity in the intermediate states. The range of possible solutions in the (p, υx)-plane is marked by the shaded region. Whereas the pressure in the intermediate state can take any value between pL and pR, the normal flow velocity can be arbitrarily close to zero in the case of an extremely relativistic tangential flow. The values of the tangential velocity in the states L* and R* are obtained from the value of the corresponding functions of υx (see lower panel of Figure 33). The influence of initial left and right tangential velocities on the solution of a Riemann problem is enhanced in highly relativistic problems.
